05928nam a22008535i 9780231549431DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018039213  a97802315494317 a10.7312/kill191482doi  a(DE-B1597)526828  a(OCoLC)1065543743  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aBX1406.3b.F88 2019 7aREL0100002bisacsh04a282/.730905122304aThe Future of Catholicism in America /ced. by Patricia O'Connell Killen, Mark Silk. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Future of Religion in America00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tSeries Editors’ Introduction: The Future of Religion in America -- tIntroduction: The Future of Roman Catholicism in the United States: Beyond the Subculture -- t1. Catholicism Today: Adrift and/or Adjusting -- t2. Becoming Latino: The Transformation of U.S. Catholicism -- t3. Since Vatican II: American Catholicism in Transition -- t4. Who Pastors: The Priest, the Context, and the Ministry -- t5. A Pluriform Unity: A Historian’s View of the Contemporary Church -- t6. Catholic Worship in a Contentious Age -- t7. Public Catholicism: Contemporary Presence and Future Promise -- tConclusion: The Shape of the American Catholic Future -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCatholics constitute the largest religious community in the United States. Yet most American Catholics have never known a time when their church was not embroiled in controversies over liturgy, religious authority, cultural change, and gender and sexuality. Today, these arguments are taking place against the backdrop of Pope Francis’s progressive agenda and the resurgence of the clergy sexual abuse crisis. What is the future of Catholicism in America?This volume considers the prospects at a pivotal moment. Contributors—scholars from sociology, theology, religious studies, and history—look at the church’s evolving institutional structure, its increasing ethnic diversity, and its changing public presence. They explore the tensions among members of the hierarchy, between clergy and laity, and along lines of ethnicity, immigration status, class, generation, political affiliation, and degree of religious commitment. They conclude that American Catholicism’s future will be pluriform—reflecting the variety of cultural, political, ideological, and spiritual points of view that typify the multicultural, democratic society of which Catholics constitute so large a part.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Catholic.2bisacsh1 aAvella, Steven M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChinnici, Joseph P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDinges, William D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKillen, Patricia O'Connell, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMatovina, Timothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO’Connell Killen, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchuth, Katarina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSilk, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSilk, Mark, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWalsh, Andrew H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWood, Richard L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065195908iTitle is part of 